SkillNotes_T2: I am now able to stop and think about my feelings more than I did before I started this.
HowNotes_T2: Every day I now take an hour to relax. Whether it's sitting by the lake or taking a nap or working out I am now able to allow my self to relax.
BarriersNotes_T2: I wish I could plan when I get the notifications from Headspace. Most of the time when I get a notification I am busy or not in a place where I can meditate. If I could change the times of the notifications it would work better with my schedule.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: His voice is very calming and allows me to truly relax.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I set up the notifications so that I get 5 a day. I get them at times of the day when I am busy or not able to meditate.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: It didn't really affect my use of Headspace. Signing up for everything with the group helped a little bit, but not much.
GroupNotes_T2: I've been really busy and it's hard for me to add something to a daily routine. Seeing everyone else's stats makes me feel as if I'm not doing as much as I could be doing.
MotivatingGroup_T2: When people comment on my posts or post things it motivates me. It is comforting to know that other people are going through the same thing as me.
HinderingGroup_T2: No.
MedsExplain_T3: Adderall for ADD/ADHD. The change was made on 26th of november. My prescription was changed from 15mg to 20 mg
PracticeNotes_T3: I  have been using headspace for the last 2 months. I havent been using it as much as I planned or hoped for, but when I really need it I use it.
SkillNotes_T3: Instead of stressing over events right away I now take time to think about the situation. Instead of thinking that I am stressed and there's nothing to do, I now know there is so much you can do and it's normal to feel that way.
HowNotes_T3: There was a couple family emergencies this semester when I had to go home and deal with quite a bit of emotions. I was able to step back from everything and just think about how I am feeling and what I can do to help others feel better.
BarriersNotes_T3: No
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I used the anxiety pack and I am currently using  the motivation pack. I found that if I forgot or couldn't find time to meditate for a few days I would forget what was talked about in the last session and I liked that there was a recap before each new sessions.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I like that you can set how many reminders you would like per day. But, I think it would be more helpful if you could adjust when you got the notifications. Often I would get the notification in class or when I'm studying and it was hard to make time. If I got it when I couldn't meditate I usually forgot about it until the next notification.

SkillNotes_T2: Using some of the breathing and awareness exercises I am able to step back a little in certain situations, and calm myself down, and realize that I am not my thoughts.
HowNotes_T2: I use them when Im having anxiety attacks or when I feel really overwhelmed with everything going on in my life.
BarriersNotes_T2: Not any I can think of, no.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I really enjoyed the analogy where your thoughts are just cars passing by and you acknowledge them but don't try to interfere. I also really like the exercise where you imagine a steady flow of air filling you up and flowing through your body.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: The most helpful part for me was that they described different ways to think about meditation that made it seem more accessible to me
GroupNotes_T2: I think the idea of supporting each other is really good, but its hard to post in it every day or stay motivated to comment, because I'm being honest, I'm more focused on my own meditation experience and I'm not necessarily interested in other people's experiences.
MotivatingGroup_T2: The fact that we were supposed to.
HinderingGroup_T2: Not really.
PracticeNotes_T3: I haven't done any other apps or exercises other than the headspace ones.
SkillNotes_T3: I have used some of the techniques in my daily life such as the breathing ones. Those skills really help when I'm having an anxiety attack and allow me to take control of my breathing.
HowNotes_T3: I got anxious about coming to the EEG session because im not good at sitting still for this long so i was doing the breathing exercises that i got from the anxiety pack on my way over here.
BarriersNotes_T3: No theres nothing that makes it hard to engage
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I didn't like the one thats supposed to help you sleep because it actually made me more aware/ awake and i couldn't fall asleep for awhile. I really like the idea of the stress one because its like filling up your body with air and i also like the anxiety one because the focusing on my breathing has a big effect on my anxiety.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: After awhile i got annoyed with all the notifications. They were nice but i had it on 5 a day and it was just a little too much. The reminder to practice was really helpful though because i don't think i would've ever remembered if my phone didn't remind me everyday.

TherapyExplain_T2: a) 9/22-present  b) Mindfulness to work on anxiety
PracticeNotes_T2: I see a psychologist once a week.
SkillNotes_T2: I have learned to be more present.
HowNotes_T2: Sometimes, when I am stressed, I try to focus on the present stimuli.
BarriersNotes_T2: It's hard to keep up with it everyday because no one is directly holding me accountable
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I am listening to the anxiety one, and sometimes, I find the skills hard to apply in the moment.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I wish I could set multiple reminders to meditate.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I wish we could meet with the Headspace members more
GroupNotes_T2: I like the positive quotes.
MotivatingGroup_T2: Not much
HinderingGroup_T2: There were a lot of posts.
TherapyExplain_T3: a. every Friday for an hour since mid-September   b. humanistic, focused on anxiety
PracticeNotes_T3: we do a mindfulness practice every Friday in therapy
SkillNotes_T3: i have learned more about being mindful and how to address my anxious thoughts in terms of just accepting rather than changing
HowNotes_T3: when I feel down, I try ti remain present within the moment
BarriersNotes_T3: no one is there to hold you accountable. this is why face-to-face interaction works better for me. also, being thrown in a Facebook group with a bunch of people I did not know and being expected to share personal thoughts about myself was weird
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: i liked the shorter mindfulness exercises because they were really easy to do right before bed.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: i wish i could set multiple reminders to meditate. One feature I found irritating was being expected to calm down during the single ones for high intensity emotions
TherapyExplain_T4: Individual therapy from the middle of September through the middle of December Humanistic approach focused on mindfulness to cope with anxiety, specifically around relationships
PracticeNotes_T4: None just therapy

SkillNotes_T2: I learned how being in the present is very important not only for optimum focus but for the well being of your mind as well.
HowNotes_T2: Whenever I am stressed about something, my mind tends to wonder from what I am doing now, which might be studying or paying attention in class. I remind myself that my thoughts are not me and I have the ability to choose not to think that way.
BarriersNotes_T2: Using Headspace every day can be tedious. Sometimes I don't want to use my phone and just be in the space around me. In other words, I like meditating and reflecting by myself.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: The patience and anxiety packet really stuck to me. Patient had to do with being patient and kind to yourself first so that you can be patient and empathetic towards other. The anxiety packet helped me focus on the here and now so that I don't have to worry about the future.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I liked to see that it wasn't only me using it and maybe benefiting from it. Sometimes, it was nice reading the reminders, but I sometimes forget about it because I am busy with school.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I personally thought that more could have been done with the peer group. In the beginning, we all made efforts to contributes on our thoughts. But it was hard sharing more things about our experiences when we barely knew each other. I would rather prefer to get to know the members of the groups before sharing intimate stuff about me and my thoughts about depression and anxiety. But the facebook was a good way to help motivate me when others post about their experiences.
GroupNotes_T2: I felt motivated once other people posted. I posted several times and it was a good way for me to write things out and put my feelings into words.
MotivatingGroup_T2: Seeing how others are progressing by using the app.
HinderingGroup_T2: No one really posting things.
SkillNotes_T3: Being able to know that I can have control over my feelings and how I can choose to react to my thoughts.
HowNotes_T3: When I am feeling overwhelmed with school, I take a break and use mindfulness to bring me back and more determined rather than helpless.
BarriersNotes_T3: Being too overwhelmed with life and not setting time to do it.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I liked the patient pack because it relates to me more.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: Eyeing that other people do it is motivating.

PracticeNotes_T2: For the in-person guided and non-guided mindfulness, as well as the other category, I practice yoga on regular basis. I normally participate in a group class, but there are nights were I do some movements and breathing on my own to help my mind and body.
SkillNotes_T2: Through Headspace I have definitely gained more of an awareness of my breathing and how it impacts my mind and my body. I find this extremely prevalent in my practice of yoga.
HowNotes_T2: Throughout my practice of yoga, I find myself reflecting on the things I have learned using Headspace and that has really allowed me to deepen my practice.
BarriersNotes_T2: Time is definitely a barrier that is more difficult to overcome that I initially thought. Even with multiple reminders throughout the day to get some Headspace, the timing is just never right. Then, by the time I notice I haven't taken 10 yet, it's past midnight, which means it didn't count for the previous day.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I have gone through the basics and I am on day 4 of the stress pack. I like to do the minis on days where I know I really do need Headspace, but also know that I won't have time to do a full 10 minute session.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I didn't find any of the features annoying. The reminders to take 10 and get Headspace really force me to try and find a time to do it.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: The orientation overall was helpful in terms of setting up Headspace and the Facebook group, but I did run really long.
GroupNotes_T2: I think that it's nice to know that I have a group of people I can go to if I have questions, but other than that I don't get much use out of the Facebook group. I check it daily, but most of the posts are from the admin account.
MotivatingGroup_T2: I want to see if my peers had posted anything.
HinderingGroup_T2: There really isn't anything hindering me from it.
PracticeNotes_T3: n/a
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned that it is okay to pause and take a moment to rest my mind and sit with my thoughts rather than constantly trying to fight them.
HowNotes_T3: These skills really helped while studying for a big exam or in the midst of being overwhelmed with work or the amount of things on my constantly growing to-do list.
BarriersNotes_T3: I definitely found that if I had to do an exercise that involved closing my eyes, it was hard to do in a more public area like the bus or the L, which was a time that I would have liked to be able to do these exercises.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I went through the basics pack and some of the stress pack, but I found that it was extremely difficult to get the longer sessions in because there are always  people around me and I really wanted the exercise to be an environment that I could get the most of the exercise. Having a roommate made doing this incredibly difficult because we share the space and are usually in conversation, so it's really hard to have ten minutes to complete an exercise. I really enjoyed the minis, they were really nice when I need a little something to calm my mind before bed or give me an extra push while doing homework.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I didn't find any of the features of Headspace to be unpleasant, they were all more motivating if anything. The biggest thing for me was the reminders. I know for a fact that if I did not have constant reminders to do these exercises, all of my numbers would have lower than they already are.
PracticeNotes_T4: Along with HeadSpace I continued my regular practice of yoga.

SkillNotes_T2: Sometimes I just really need a reminder to take a step back to focus on myself / how I'm feeling. Headspace gives me time to do just that.
BarriersNotes_T2: Sometimes I still find it hard to take time out of my day to meditate and essentially do nothing. I need to convince myself that even while meditating/using headspace, I'm being productive.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I really like the stress pack - it's exactly what I need to hear.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I thought the orientation was great! I learned a lot and had a good time hearing about the instructors' experiences and sharing my own. I wish my other peers were more willing to speak up / share.
GroupNotes_T2: Truthfully, I haven't been keeping up with the Facebook very much. I think the Mindful Ness account posts too often and it's annoying getting those notifications all the time. I do like when my peers post things. I also am not a huge fan of user stats postings, mostly because I am so behind everyone else in terms of time meditated because I forget all the time and am so incredibly busy this semester.
PracticeNotes_T3: I have been doing yoga 2-3 times a week. The instructor I regularly see is very focused on mindfulness and I always leave the class feeling refreshed and de-stressed.
SkillNotes_T3: I really like the Headspace app - I love the focus on bringing your attention to your immediate surroundings, as opposed to everything that is stressing you out. It's nice to know how to escape those unhealthy persistent thoughts.
HowNotes_T3: I can now de-stress on my own by using techniques I learned in the app. I don't always need to be listening to the classes to 'meditate' on my own.
BarriersNotes_T3: I found it hard to make time for mindfulness every day. I thought taking 10 minutes out of my day for meditiation would be easy but it weirdly wasnt. This has been the most busy semester of my college career and having so much on my plate was a barrier to meditation, although I probably needed it this semester more than ever.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I really liked the basics pack and the stress pack.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I personally hated the daily reminders. I would get them a million times a day and they were always at inconvenient times in my day.
PracticeNotes_T4: Other - I do yoga at least twice a week every week. The yoga classes I typically attend are more focused on mindfulness and full body stretches than strength.

SkillNotes_T2: Just taking a minute out of my session to let my mind wander and have all thoughts, pleasant or unpleasant to flow through and accept them
HowNotes_T2: Whenever I’m on my daily run, I let my mind wonder and as a result, it tends to blank out and do whatever it wants to do
BarriersNotes_T2: The app tends to repeat some exercises
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I really liked the Depression pack but i found some of his comments about the thoughts as being less important than what they really were a bit off-ish since I have suffered from and continue dealing with intrusive thoughts. Those thoughts can sometimes be very distressing and now that I’m better at handling them, they aren’t something that i can “let go”
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: Nothing much to comment on except for his off-ish comments sometimes
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I found all parts of the session helpful and especially the personal experiences of the researcher positively impacted my approach towards the study
PracticeNotes_T3: Daily musical meditation in order to destress
SkillNotes_T3: Just allowing myself to not try to block out the distressing thoughts and stressors but to let them flow in and out, embracing the feelings and slowly transitioning to be calm
HowNotes_T3: Whenever I feel particularly stressed out from my intrusive thoughts, I momentarily excuse myself the stress and allow myself to sense my body and the environment around and examine and cope with the stress
BarriersNotes_T3: Sometimes the narrator can be a bit insensitive when it comes to dealing with stressful thoughts as these are not thoughts that one should shut off  or easily turned them off.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I mostly listened to the Depression and Anxiety core packs. What I particularly liked about them is that I could focus on the world around me and just focus on the here and now. I was more motivated to listen to the Depression packet since I was dealing with recurring depressive thoughts and feeling at the beginning of the study. However; I didn't really like how the narrator could be a bit insensitive to depressive thoughts and moods.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: Allowing me to see on my progress and journey using the Headspace app really helped in seeing how I grew from the beginning of the study. There weren't many unpleasant features other than the occasionally insensitive comments by the narrator. Other than that, there isn't much I can comment on.
PracticeNotes_T4: I have been doing daily exercise and have practiced mediation during that time

PracticeNotes_T2: I've tried to apply some of the advice given during the headspace app like being more aware of my surroundings and trying to be present.
SkillNotes_T2: In one of the meditations he emphasized on the importance of just simply being aware of things like when you stand up or sit down. At first I found it a bit strange but I got into the habit of doing it pretty much every day and although I felt it was a little strange it forces me to recognize and be present even if it is just for that moment which I really feel like helps me be more mindful.
HowNotes_T2: I've had a pretty anxious last two weeks and have found myself using the skill of just accepting my anxious thoughts and letting them pass through without rejecting them or blocking them. Usually I just try to force myself to not think about it but this never really proves to be successful and I just end up being anxious about being anxious. By kind of accepting these thoughts I think it helps me not see them as such a bad thing and more of just a part of every day life that eventually will pass through.
BarriersNotes_T2: nope
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I really liked the everyday headspace because it's different everyday and great for the days where I'm super busy and don't have a lot of time to listen to the anxiety pack. I like the idea of the singles but I always get distracted with the other options and end up listening to something else.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I really like the mindful moments and reminders to get practice because sometimes I don't remember to use headspace but these are great at making sure I do! I also like the run streak because it keeps me motivated to keep using the app.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I definitely really liked how all of the researchers were experienced with headspace as well. It was easier to understand headspace by having them explain it rather then try to figure it out through pictures.
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned a lot about self awareness and being aware of my actions in general. Headspace has encouraged me to focus on my physical movements and placements of my body on a daily basis. I think by doing this I have been able to focus less on my anxious thoughts and being more present.
HowNotes_T3: I tend to use these skills when I'm more alone. For example, I notice myself paying more attention to my body and actions mostly while in the car, on the train, or when walking to and from class.
BarriersNotes_T3: no
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I really liked everyday headspace because it was short and different everyday. I also feel like the basic packs were really good at giving me the skills to better manage the other packs. I was most interested in the anxiety pack because that was a big reason why I joined this study and found it pretty helpful!
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I think the reminders were really helpful. I also really liked the people meditating now as well as the run streak because it motivated me to continue using headspace.

SkillNotes_T2: I have learned to take a part of my day and direct just to reflexion for myself and to disconnect a little from everything else that is happening around me.
HowNotes_T2: Just when using the app. I have tried to use it everyday whenever I am feeling overwhelmed.
BarriersNotes_T2: The practice of mindfulness starts to get a little repetitive since the recordings on the app are basically the same and that makes me lose my focus more often during the practice than it did in the beginning since it is all the same.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I do not like how repetitive the recordings are.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: Notifications are discrete and very helpful reminder to set aside time for headspace. I liked the mindful moments, not all of them made me feel better but sometimes they were encouraging.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Most helpful part of the orientation was when the researches showed us how to use the app and talked about their own personal experience.
SkillNotes_T3: Letting thoughts go and recognizing distractions as normal
HowNotes_T3: When I am feeling overwhelmed with school
BarriersNotes_T3: Headspace app is very repetitive and started to become boring after a couple of times. It seemed like another task to do other than something to help me to get better it added stress sometimes
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: disliked  the repetition. I liked the techniques and applying them outside of the app but not during the meditations.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: Streak was very good to keep me motivated

PracticeNotes_T2: I occasionally went to yoga about 2 times within the last month.
SkillNotes_T2: I'm currently on the stress pack, and it has helped a lot with my stress because it's a way for me to escape reality for a moment, and take time to evaluate my life and think about what is stressing me out so I can take those negative motions and get rid of them or try to make a positive outcome.
HowNotes_T2: Using the ability to just take a moment and realize whats happening around you and taking it into account is used when I'm with friends and I'm stressed out, it gets turned around because I try to stress less and look at everyone's point of view.
BarriersNotes_T2: No.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I found the singles very helpful because they are there for those specific moments of need in a certain area and having the concentration in a certain area was helpful. I was motivated to start stress because as a college student starting off I thought it would be most useful and it has been. I having nothing really I disliked.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: Sometimes the spaces are a bit long and I tend to dose off and forget its playing, but when I'm reminded I just get right back into it. In the everyday headspace it doesn't really tell you when the session is ending like the packs do, so they is something that is a bit bothersome. Everything else was great.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Everything ran smoothly at the orientation, no need for improvement.
PracticeNotes_T3: Non guided meditations included me having some time to myself a few times a week just to think and reflect.
SkillNotes_T3: Some skills I have developed includes being more patient and aware of situations around me. I learned to take into account what is happening around me, accepting that sometimes you are unable to change what the outcome of a situation is and learn to just live with it and take into account that it has happened.
HowNotes_T3: In times of feeling anxious or angry because of the way something works out I have learned to just think about the situation or event and turn it into something positive by thinking of positive thoughts, or just simply being aware that it is happening, knowing there may not be anything I can do to control it.
BarriersNotes_T3: No
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: One of my favorite packs was patience because that was an aspect I had been struggling with before coming into the program. I now have a better understanding of patience and how it effects me in my daily life. Patience to me is a feeling that I am now able to control by just taking a moment to think about how what I may say or do will effect others.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The pauses were the only thing I can say were a bit annoying. They were nice at times to just take a moment and reflect and think about in the moment situations but were not harmful at all. What I valued were the minis a lot because during times that I had feelings all of a sudden and didn't want to continue in a pack I was doing, I was able to focus in on a specific subject that I was struggling with,

SkillNotes_T2: Just to talk a minute to relax and focus on myself.
HowNotes_T2: When I feel overwhelmed I just take a few deep breaths and close my eyes.
BarriersNotes_T2: N/A
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: Singles are my favorite bc you’re still taking time for your self but slightly active. Not a fan of the others but still slightly useful.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: Like seeing how other people are doing. Don’t really need to know what packs they’ve done.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Don’t need copies of the PowerPoint. Nice meeting everyone. Felt really long.
MotivatingGroup_T2: Never really felt motivated liked doing it on my own.
HinderingGroup_T2: Not a fan of Facebook.
SkillNotes_T3: Just being calm and focused on myself
HowNotes_T3: Usually I practice before bed as it helps me sleep better more times than not.
BarriersNotes_T3: I find a lot of the packages are to repetitive in headspace
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I loved the SOS packages I wish there were more as those were my favorite because I feel like they all sound different and are what I need in that moment.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I liked seeing how many people were meditating. The streaks helped as well as notifications. Videos I liked but would skip.

SkillNotes_T2: I have been better able to compartmentalize emotions in order to synthesize them more effectively.
HowNotes_T2: When I feel like I am having an 'emotional crisis,' I feel well equipped to be able to handle my emotions and work through them in a rational and calculated manner.
BarriersNotes_T2: I do not find the Facebook group to be as impactful as it might be intended due to the fact that I'm not a serial Facebook user.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I very much enjoy the singles packs, especially 'falling asleep' and some of the ones geared toward unwinding. I often find those more helpful than the basic or core packs because I like they feel more tailored to how I feel in the moment rather than working through a larger underlying emotion like in the core packs.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I enjoy being able to view my run streak and other stats because it makes me feel accomplished.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Copy of slides maybe wasn't necessary. Overall maybe could have been shorter. I think there was already a shared understanding of the benefits of mindfulness seeing as that's why most participants chose to be a part of the study.
GroupNotes_T2: I enjoyed being able to see the group stats to see what we all had in common for the week, but I don't think that the Facebook group is necessarily my preferred form of a motivational group.
MotivatingGroup_T2: Email reminders
HinderingGroup_T2: I am not a frequent Facebook user.
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned how to better manage, compartmentalize, and assess my emotions
HowNotes_T3: If I encounter a stressful situation, I am more inclined to take a step back to think about my emotions before reacting immediately
BarriersNotes_T3: I am not a serial Facebook user, so I did not feel actively engaged in the group. This did not affect my use of headspace or the attitude towards the study,
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I most enjoyed the 'falling asleep' single. It definitely put me in the right mindset for sleep and helped me fall asleep faster. I also appreciated that most sessions had different time options. The 'run streak' also kept me motivated
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: Run streak is a great feature that kept me motivated. I didn't feel the need for the mindful moments or daily notifications; I rarely forgot about the app over the course of the day.

SkillNotes_T2: Not forcing my mind to behave in any way or another, rather gently brining it to a proper meditation place
HowNotes_T2: I like clearing my mind right before an exam so I can calm my nerves
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: So far I have stuck with the basics and I've done a speciality one. I like having just a generic session. They usually are shorter too so I can fit them into my schedule better.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: The only thing I didn't find helpful were the app reminders, because then it makes mindfulness seem like a chore rather than something I do when   I need it.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Most helpful parts were helping us set up the app. Least value was playing the videos that we were going to watch anyways in the basic pack. Not that it wasn't valuable, but it was something we were going to watch anyways
GroupNotes_T2: The stats posting makes me realize that I use the app less than everyone else and I felt bad that I wasn't finding more time, but I just reminded myself that everyone's needs/schedules are different
MotivatingGroup_T2: Learning more about my group mates
HinderingGroup_T2: no
SkillNotes_T3: To not just suppress negative thoughts, but rather notice them and let them pass by
HowNotes_T3: In stressful situations I have tried to remember what I learned in the app to calm myself down such as before tests
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I liked the basics because they were generic and could apply to any day. The minis were good when I was in a rush
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I don't have much to say: I really liked the set up and the features of the app. Maybe if some of the more specialized packs were shorter, they would have been easier to fit into my daily routine

PracticeNotes_T2: I participate in a weekly restorative yoga class that incorporates some guided meditation along with my headspace usage.
SkillNotes_T2: As helpful as the headspace app is, I find that in-person guided meditation seems to impact me more strongly.
HowNotes_T2: I believe my relationship with a close friend has improved because of my work on the Acceptance meditation pack - I've been trying to focus on appreciating how things are in the now instead of worrying about the past or future.
BarriersNotes_T2: Facebook is convenient to form groups, but I think people would be more willing to post/talk in the group if it was in more of a group message format, so it felt more like you simply texting back and forth like many of us do in every day life already.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: The shorter meditations like the singles or the everyday headspace seem much less burdensome than the packs where the minimum time is 10 minutes. Refreshers seem to help me more than trying to concentrate for >10 minutes.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: The mindful moments don't seem to do anything for me, because I spend my time reflecting on quotes/notes like those during my sessions anyways. The notifications help a bit, but all in all my participation depends on my personal motivation, and a notification can't always provide that.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: The orientation was generally very helpful because it introduced how to use the app itself and what the purpose of the study is. However, I found that it was much longer than what I think is necessary because many of the topics were repeated throughout orientation.
GroupNotes_T2: The user stats postings were motivating yet they also made me a bit anxious when I knew I wasn't using the app as regularly as I should be.
MotivatingGroup_T2: When I had a good streak going on headspace, that motivated me to want to post/reply in the page because I felt like I was really participating in the study well.
HinderingGroup_T2: Overall, I personally don't think the facebook group adds anything to my benefit and I would rather hold myself accountable for doing my daily meditation rather than feel like I need to post to a page for no reason other than to participate.
PracticeNotes_T3: I go to a restorative yoga  class every weekend (once a week) that involves guided thoughtfulness and some meditation. I also try to use mindfulness techniques frequently in my everyday life (deep breathing, thoughtfulness).
SkillNotes_T3: Headspace has helped me with skills such a stepping back from a situation and thinking through events rather than having a strong emotional reaction right away.  General, everyday mindfulness has seemed to be more impactful on my life compared to the actual meditation sessions through the app.
HowNotes_T3: I sometimes get anxious and have trouble breathing or thinking straight as a result, and using the app directly helps calm me down, or if I don't have access to the app then I use the skills I've learned from using the app.
BarriersNotes_T3: I find that face-to-face meditation and group relaxation/mindfulness is more helpful to me personally. Being in a room all by myself with a person speaking to me through an app makes it harder for me to stay engaged and concentrate.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: The quick sessions such as the minis or the everyday headspace were much easier to fit into a busy day or get it over with if I'm just not feeling like doing headspace. The core packs and other packs specified for a particular topic are more helpful than the basics pack, in my opinion. The basic pack didn't do much for me and I think that only one basic session is needed.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The practice reminders unfortunately did not motivate me as I Initially thought they would. Those reminders along with mindful moments quotes usually got lost in my notifications and if I did see them they would sometimes just make me more stressed about how I had not meditated that day.

GroupNotes_T2: I liked our introductions, but after that no one really posted again.
SkillNotes_T3: I've learned that I need to take my time with things and take care of myself.
HowNotes_T3: I'm trying to get more active and hang out with my friends more often.
BarriersNotes_T3: Sometimes it is hard for me to take the time to really step back and focus on mindfulness, simply because of my school work.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I did like the some of the singles, such as the sleep session. It helped me calm down and rest my hyperactive mind.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The videos did an excellent job at explaining each exercise and stating what they want you to take away from it.

PracticeNotes_T2: I usually do the singles lately for Headspace. Because of Headspace, I began to reflect more on my actions and how I'm feeling as a means to calm down if I'm in a place where I can't use Headspace.
SkillNotes_T2: I really liked the visualization method, where we just imagine a warm sunlight above us. There are also things like focusing on your breathing and just letting thoughts pass by or even just recognizing you're thinking or feeling.
HowNotes_T2: For the past couple of weeks, I haven't necessarily been feeling very well emotionally, but that's when I started recognizing that I'm having these feelings or these thoughts. Then I stop myself and just let the thought go. Other times, I find myself getting distracted and I recognize it so I return back to what I was doing.
BarriersNotes_T2: N/A
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I used a lot of the SOS singles because of the rough few weeks, and it helped me a lot with calming down and breathing. Although, I do have to admit, sometimes it becomes really hard when I'm under too many emotions to just let them pass by. I also used a lot of the minis in case I got busy during the day and forgot, mainly the unwind and breathe ones because I need to relax. As for the packs, I made it all the way to day 13 (I believe) in the self-esteem pack. While I like the tools they provide in that pack, I'm not entirely sure if it's exactly boosting my self-esteem.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I don't think I ran into anything that was unpleasant while using this application.
GroupNotes_T2: I think the thing is that the group isn't very active. I try my best to be active here and there, but usually no one responds so it becomes a little un-motivating to attempt to post and comment as much as I can. Still, I like being able to leave some positive comments here and there. I tried doing that both for others and myself because I think maybe striving to be positive as well can change my mindset, too, and it can do the same for others. Although... I don't think I really discuss much about mindfulness unless I'm replying to the admin's posts.
MotivatingGroup_T2: At the beginning of the research, I think I was very motivated when someone would reply/post  in the group.
HinderingGroup_T2: Not that anything hindered me from the group, but I tend to not use facebook often anyways, so I tend to forget to log in.
SkillNotes_T3: I liked learning about just slowly bringing your mind back to focus, and the visualizing tool. The visualizing tool was refreshing. I also loved when I was able to let my mind wander in the exercises because it was like taking a breath in the exercise before continuing again. I think it helped me focus more that way.
HowNotes_T3: Oftentimes now, I start noting and realizing when my thoughts and feelings have wandered and that generally helps me focus my mind back to what I was doing.
BarriersNotes_T3: I realize that after break, I started to use it a lot less so it was more of my choice. I think what happened was that my days become extremely busy that I wasn't able to make time to use Headspace. And then for the group, it was hard to get motivated to post more frequently when not many other people were posting as well, so I lost motivation to really participate.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I used the self-esteem one and a lot of the SOS singles. The SOS ones were nice to listen to when I was in a state of panic because it's calming to listen to and it helps me focus on something else. I tend to use those the most whenever I feel like something is wrong and it's short too so it works well. Then the self esteem is nice too. I didn't finish it but the tools provided that I used was calming and helped me focus more in my day to day life.
TherapyExplain_T4: Between 4/9 and 4/30 on Mondays for an hour; Only three sessions; Focused on increasing mood and boosting confidence.
@3Goals: Connecting with others; emotion regulation; stress-reduction/relaxation

SkillNotes_T2: I think being able to acknowledge my thoughts but being able to let them go and learning how to do that is really helpful in times of negative thoughts.

SkillNotes_T3: taking a step back and looking at situations without judgment

SkillNotes_T2: The small reminders throughout the day with quick phrases or quotes about mindfulness really offer great opportunities to assess myself right there in the moment and reflect on how that phrase affects me. They're like reminders to check in with yourself.
HowNotes_T2: I remember that having thoughts that distress you or are concerning are not inherently bad. It is enough to notice them, then let them go.
BarriersNotes_T2: I find it extremely hard to find even 3 or 5 minutes to engage in the app, but I feel that this is more a fault of my own than any fault of the app.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: The minis are great when 3 or 5 minutes seem too long to be away from your task.
SkillNotes_T3: I think my favorite part was the grounding exercises at the beginning of each meditation. It's very helpful to bring yourself out of your head and into the physical space you occupy.
HowNotes_T3: When I become overwhelmed, I have noticed that I now take a deep breath before continuing on, whereas before I would often let the frustration get to me.
BarriersNotes_T3: The audio aspect is difficult overcome in the dorm. I personally prefer not to use headphones, so that was slightly difficult when sharing a space. However, if I had my own space, it would be a perfect tool.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I made it through the basics pack and some of the anxiety pack. I felt most motivated to listen to the anxiety pack, but I wanted to get through the basics first so I could establish that foundation. I also loved the minis because they were very very short, but a great way to check in with yourself if you don't have a lot of time.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The silent portions of the meditation actually made me quite sleepy when they were long. I loved that they give you a total for minutes meditated. That was really cool to see.

SkillNotes_T2: Specifically through the Headspace app, I have learned about a technique called 'noting'. I tend to be a stressed and distracted person, and this technique has really helped me to notice the fact that I am feeling these things, but not become completely overwhelmed by them. I am definitely able to focus a lot more in class and in general, though I am still a work-in-progress.
HowNotes_T2: Like I mentioned before, I have been able to be more attentive in class, and I notice my emotions and thoughts more instead of letting myself go off on a tangent and judging my thoughts.
BarriersNotes_T2: The only thing that is difficult for me personally is getting myself to do a full ten minutes every day. Although ten minutes is hardly any time at all, it still seems like a large task I have to 'get through' rather than just enjoy.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: Although I haven't been able to fully commit to a pack yet, I personally find the singles to be very beneficial. Finishing a whole pack overwhelms me slightly, so the everyday Headspace and the minis really help me to destress.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I think what has helped me most to get me to use headspace is the peer support group, and having the different friends tabs so I can keep up with what other people are doing. Knowing how many people are meditating, and how much the average person meditates helps me to set goals for myself. I also really lik
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I think orientation was very helpful, it was a bit long, but I don't think much needs to be cut or added.
GroupNotes_T2: I really think that having the peer support group is what motivates me to keep doing Headspace. Sometimes I find myself discouraging myself and questioning why I am putting time into this, put my peers have reminded me to stay patient and that learning mindfulness comes with time. Also knowing that they are in it with me and going through the same things helps a lot. The stats posting helped, I didn't feel stressed at all seeing them. I also know that mindfulness is not a competition, so I didn't feel competitive in any way.
MotivatingGroup_T2: Other people posting and replying. I know that at least one other person will post if I do, and I always get a few likes and a comment so that encourages me to kee
HinderingGroup_T2: No, I've always felt fine about posting. I don't really have much to say about Headspace since you don't experience much change right away.
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned more about the noting technique that headspace promotes in guided meditation and I have definitely improved on noticing when I am distracted and being able to let go of negative thoughts.
HowNotes_T3: In class I will sometimes become distracted and I am able to recognize the distraction and move on and focus again. I have also been able to let go of more negative thoughts I have about myself throughout my day to day life.
BarriersNotes_T3: It was difficult at times to motivate myself to do an entire 10 minute meditation but having the short SOS meditations were very helpful.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I really enjoyed singles and minis and the sleep sounds, they really helped me unwind and de-stress, as well as inspire me to do longer meditations because some were thought-provoking and very positive.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The reminders to get headspace were eventually not very helpful, and I found the run streak to be a little stressful to maintain. Having friends' stats available was really helpful.

SkillNotes_T2: I have learned that I should take a step back in my busy life. Sometimes throughout the day it is important to breathe and take a break. And sometimes in these times, I will do a headspace session.
HowNotes_T2: I have used it throughout the day but especially at night. I feel like after a long day, all the work can be overwhelming and that when I feel it's a good time to take a break.
BarriersNotes_T2: Sometimes it's hard to do it daily and listen to the same voice over and over again.

ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I found that having a variety of packs to choose from was really helpful. Because on different days, I would need to deal with a different issue. I thought it was a bit repetitive sometimes which made it difficult to keep up.

HinderingGroup_T2: Just not having much to say about my experience.

SkillNotes_T3: I have learned to focus on meditation whenever I decide to do a session. In the past, I was aware of meditation steps but never actually utilised them until the Headspace app.
HowNotes_T3: When: When I feel distracted or overwhelmed before and during a class or before I begin to work on an assignment.    Where: Quiet places or any places within my own comfort zone, with few distractions and noises.    How: Meditate for 5-10 minutes as guided in the app, even without the app just sit and meditate

Comments: I like this study and how it all falls under the same general umbrella for each participant, but each participant is also able to individualize the experience.

The run streak was also very helpful because it helped to make a visual representation of how well I have been doing in my meditation and it feels nice to have a

SkillNotes_T2: Noting technique, deep breathing
BarriersNotes_T2: The facebook group isn't very helpful and seems more like a chore than something that helps
GroupNotes_T2: I felt inspired and yet often felt guilty or anxious because I would forget to post or reply to people's posts.
HinderingGroup_T2: I don't like the Facebook app so I don't use it very often.

Comments: I really enjoy meditating and practicing mindfulness and i feel like I feel better after each session. The most difficult part is staying consistent with the meditations throughout my busy schedule.
SkillNotes_T2: I’ve learned better breathing techniques that I can use when I am in stressful situations like counting my breaths. I also enjoy doing the body scan technique so i can really take notice of my body and how i am feeling. I also like the technique of not labeling my emotions as good or bad just letting them pass.
HowNotes_T2: I’ve definitely used the counting my breaths technique in order to try to balance myself in a stressful situation like taking a test.
BarriersNotes_T2: N/A
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I don’t think any of the features were hurtful at all. I enjoyed looking at the stats because it encouraged me to hold myself accountable and try to keep growing those numbers. I also think that the reminders to meditate were helpful because sometimes I would forget or would need that extra push to medita
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I think that the biggest thing I benefited from in the orientation group was the goal discussion because it gave me ideas for myself and different perspectives and slowed me to compare my challenges and not feel like I was the only one experiencing things.
MotivatingGroup_T2: I think reading other peoples posts motivated me the most because it helped me feel like i wasn’t doing this alone ans other people were working towards similar
HinderingGroup_T2: I think what hinders me the most is just a busy schedule and a lack of motivation to do things on certain days.
HowNotes_T3: Using breathing techniques, noting techniques, trying to take breaks throughout the day to just sit and observe my body and thoughts
BarriersNotes_T3: N/A
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I think it was valuable to track my own progress and keep track of what i have done, and it was helpful to see others progress to encourage myself to do more.

Comments: I feel as though this program has really helped me focus on what is important in life and how to be more mindful in my every day life. When I feel really overwhelmed, it's nice to just recognize those feelings and allow myself to reflect on them instead of letting them overpower my day.
SkillNotes_T2: I have started the managing anxiety pack that has really helped with my school-related anxiety. I learned how to recognize that anxiety is a common feeling and it is something that you can recognize and except, but move past and not let it get in the way of your current activities. I also learned how to focus more on my breathing when I am anxious, to get myself to calm down if I am feeling
HowNotes_T2: I have used these skills a lot the night before an exam. It is very common for me to get last minute panics the night before an exam so instead of having that feeling overtake the rest of my night, I simply reflect on all that I have done to prepare and just take a step back to allow myself to feel those feelings before moving on.
BarriersNotes_T2: No! I feel like this program has been very interactive and if anything, I could be a lot more active on the Facebook page.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I am working on the managing anxiety pack now and it really has helped me regain balance of my emotions. I just started the focus pack as well which really helped clear my mind before getting on with the tasks of the day.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: The reminders to practice were sort of hard for me to utilize as I have a different schedule almost every day, so it was nice to see the reminder to practice but was very easy to brush off. I really enjoyed the stats since it motivated me to want to meditate more to see how much my practicing has increased
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: The most helpful parts were having the accounts set up together, so if we had any problems we could seek help. It was also helpful to hear past experiences and to be able to meet our group during the orientation and chat with them. I did not find anything to not be helpful, as everything was in place to help us succeed.
GroupNotes_T2: The most positive aspects were being able to share my experiences with my peers and having them comment back their feedback and experiences. The user stat postings made me more motivated to want to mediate more.
MotivatingGroup_T2: I think it was seeing the posts and getting the notifications about the posts that motivated me, however I think I could be more active on the page itself.
HinderingGroup_T2: No not at all, everything seemed to make me want to go on the Facebook site especially the notifications on my phone.
PracticeNotes_T3: I generally like to just sit and reflect on aspects of my life a few times a week. For example, I will sit in a quiet space for 5 minutes and just reflect on the good and bad that have happened that week and just absorb the f
SkillNotes_T3: I learned to be more aware of my feelings in my every day life. As someone who is always busy and constantly worrying about others in my life, Headspace helped me to reflect on my own senses whether it be touch, hearing, etc. Whenever I had the time to meditate, I felt a lot more peace and focus that day because I br
HowNotes_T3: Whenever I'm studying and feel overwhelmed, I like to just take a short 2-3 minute break to remember that my feelings are valid and that I will be able to overcome this short feeling. I also like to take in nature a lot more when going for walks and just feeling present in the moment.
BarriersNotes_T3: Not at all! I feel as though I could have been more active with my Headspace usage and within the Facebook group, but I did make time for it when I was able to.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I used the managing anxiety and focus packs and really enjoyed them both. The managing anxiety pack allowed me to be more accepting of the feelings that I was having and just relax my mind. The focus pack brought me a lot of encouragement to stay present with my tasks. I had used SOS once when I was feeling very stressed out, and it was able to reset my mood and brought me a lot of peace.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The reminder were slightly valuable, but it was hard to pay attention to it at times because I had a different schedule almost every day. The stats and people meditating tab was really motivating for me because I enjoyed sending little words of affirmation to those in my team and it was nice to see how everyone was managing their headspace time.

PracticeNotes_T2: I set aside 15 minutes a day to sit and reflect on how I'm feeling
Comments: I like it but I wish we had more group interaction, as much as we all have said we want to be active on facebook we haven't. I wish we could see each other in person because I think we would get so much more out of this.
SkillNotes_T2: I have learned to be more mindful of my feeling and have taken time out of my day to reflect on how I'm feeling
HowNotes_T2: I breathe more and tell myself that I am doing a good job, in general I have just been kinder to myself.
BarriersNotes_T2: I hate using facebook and no one posts on it which makes me not want to post on it cause that's awkward. I wish we were in person because then I think I would be more open about experiences, doing it over zoom is really awkward.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I find the focus and anxiety/stress packs the most helpful. I don't get a ton out of there basics because they're just generic in my opinion and don't do anything the only helpful one was the first because it really taught me hoe to meditate and get in a mindfulness mood
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I hate the silent spaces because I can't keep focused during the silence and my mind wanders until he starts to talk again then I can refocus but its just so distracting.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: The most important parts were meeting my group members but I wish everything was set up ahead of time (ie sending codes and getting facebook group together)
GroupNotes_T2: I like when other people post but I kinda hate when the smile group posts because I think the inspirational things are so cheesy. I like the stats because they motivate me to do more mostly because I'm competitive.
MotivatingGroup_T2: The push notifications because I wanted them off of my home screen in all honesty, but I like when other people posted
HinderingGroup_T2: the fact that no one posts makes me not want to post
PracticeNotes_T3: I have taken about 10 minutes out of my day to stop and be aware of what is going on in my life
SkillNotes_T3: I am able to recognize when I am not doing well and take the time to step back and practice self care
HowNotes_T3: I am more aware about what is going on around me and I feel more present in my everyday life
BarriersNotes_T3: Not seeing people in real life has been hard and I feel like I would have done better with more in-person meetings, but obviously that wasn't possible so the zoom meetings were the next best thing
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: the focus pack and sos mini were the most helpful and I wanted to do the focus pack the most. the basic pack was not helpful because it was so repetitive and predictable and never could keep me engaged.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: the reminder to use headspace was annoying because it only could be set for one time, which never really worked for all days. I loved the mini pack because it really helped in times of crisis and calmed me down. I liked when other people would say hi or check in with the buddy feature because it reminded me that I wasn't alone in this.

Comments: I am truly enjoying this program and have seen quite a difference in myself regarding some things. I am more patient and less anxious, although it has not helped my depression much.
SkillNotes_T2: I have learned to let go of a lot of my thoughts. It is not easy and I tend to forget to do such, but when I remember to, I am now capable of doing such (which is new for me).
HowNotes_T2: I was extremely stressed before my exam this week and instead of freaking out, I took the time to meditate and be mindful of my emotions, thoughts, and feelings.
BarriersNotes_T2: It is difficult having it online, I wish we could meet in person.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I listened to the Stress Pack and I found it extremely helpful in relieving the tension I felt from the work load. Online school is a struggle and this meditation has helped me through some tough moments.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I think all of the features are honestly great and offer a great variety of options. I haven't been exploring much because I am already overwhelmed as is but I definitely plan on discovering some new packs.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Orientation was really great and I would love to hear more facts about meditation and its effects on mental health. Other than that, I think it had everything needed. The most helpful parts of orientation was the interaction part where we could talk to one another and express our goals and expectations.
GroupNotes_T2: The sense of community during out meets have been the most beneficial experience of the group so far. I wish we could meet in person because Facebook groups feel quite isolated but with the circumstances we have, I think this is running pretty great. I really do enjoy the motivational quotes on the FB page.
MotivatingGroup_T2: I am most motivated when somebody posts something about themselves and it is not just the moderator posting a motivational quote.
HinderingGroup_T2: I think a lack of activity from the other members made me feel ridiculous for posting more than I already did.
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned to better let go of disturbing thoughts but still addressing past traumas that have been repressed. It is most definitely not a perfect process and my depression is nowhere near alleviated, but I can finally take a look at my thoughts and past! With more practice and time, I am sure I can handle those
HowNotes_T3: When I am going to sleep and feel my mind racing, I began to take deep breaths and relaxing parts of my body one by one, letting my thoughts drift by; as a result, I have begun to sleep much better.
BarriersNotes_T3: I think it was a bit difficult to stay engaged when I could not see my peer groups in person... I really do not like zoom calls and interaction through a screen, therefore it was becoming difficult to connect, especially towards the end.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I started off with the "Letting Go of Stress" pack then moved on to some sleeping singles that have helped me significantly with my insomnia. I did not dislike anything, I believe everything was quite good and helpful whenever I could get around to meditating.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I think the app is quite great, although I must admit there were moments where I felt guilty for not meditating with the reminder of how much I meditated in the past... but I would not say that was necessarily harmful, I'm simply a person that feels guilty for not completing personal tasks. I do enjoy the communication aspect of the app where you can send supportive stickers to your buddies.

MedsExplain_T2: I stopped taking fluoxetine about three weeks ago.

Comments: I think that for Peer Groups we should definitely try to make it less formal. There were a lot of times where it felt like a discussion than getting to know the actual people who are participating in the study. I think that helping to make it an informal talk within the topic of headspace is necessa
SkillNotes_T2: I’ve definitely worked on focus more than other programs, but I’ve also looked at ones for sleep and stress. I’ve learned to take a step back and pause, which I’ve always had trouble doing, not to reflect on my regrets but also to breathe and focus on the present.
HowNotes_T2: When i’m doing my homework, the app helped me to solitarily stop myself when I’m about to get stressed so that I can get up, stretch, and let the thoughts flow out.
BarriersNotes_T2: As I mentioned before, simply the lack of conversation in the Peer Groups had made it unnatural but other than that, Headspace actually removes a lot of barriers in day-to-day life.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I listened to packs on focus, sleep, and stress when using Headspace and I originally went into the program with the desire of learning how to focus. I really liked that pack and I felt that they were more trying to bring peace to mind to ALLOW me to focus rather than try to subconsciously trick me into focusing. Headspace puts a lot of the responsibility on me, but what’s nice about it is that is gives me the ability to follow up on those responsibilities; the app is more like a personal trainer.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: All-in-all, each feature gave me a push to continue. This is truly like a personal trainer for your mental health in that with features like how many minutes you’ve done, how many packs you’ve completed, or what your peers have accomplished, it reminds you that you’ve made progress. However small the
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I think that the process of obtaining an account was quite lengthy. Maybe having accounts already made for the participants would streamline the process more? Regardless, it was still an overall helpful orientation.
GroupNotes_T2: I think the group idea is pretty nice and helps you connect with everyone in the study. What I love most is the meetup that we have every month because I find that to be a fun way to get to know my peers well. I didn’t find anything necessarily hindering, especially the user stat postings as they just helped me feel that I was just like everyone else.
MotivatingGroup_T2: When I saw another peer’s post.
HinderingGroup_T2: When it was just a post from the Loyola SMiLe page.
SkillNotes_T3: Just how to clear my mind/let thoughts flow. I really used to have that problem so I’m glad that’s one of the basic skills that Headspace taught me.
HowNotes_T3: I usually used them when I wished to wind and calm down so I can just be in the moment.
BarriersNotes_T3: I felt that the nature of Headspace was beneficial and smooth, overall
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: The focus pack really helped with my problem when it comes to me being easily distracted. It helps to clear the mind and prepare to actually do work. I found it extremely helpful.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: Being able to see other people’s stats really helped me stay focus and/or feel better if my stats weren’t as high as I wanted them to be. The sense of togetherness that I felt while I was engaging in Headspace really helped me to continue on with the study.

SkillNotes_T2: Meditation before sleep time

SkillNotes_T2: I have learned to acknowledge my thoughts and emotions is a positive way that helps me to get back on track rather than ignoring them.
HowNotes_T2: I use mindfulness and acknowledgment when I feel anxious or stressed out. I try to take a step back and relax until I feel that I am ready to continue with my task or day.
BarriersNotes_T2: Sometimes I feel that it would be better if some of the mediations meant for anxiety were shorter because I sometimes find it difficult to be still and focused for longer than a few minutes.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I have found that the SOS, stress, anxiety, focus, and adapting to change packs have been most relevant to me because they are specific to how I am feeling in that moment. I found the adapting to change and anxiety packs to be best, especially in our current situation of a global pandemic.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I personally didn’t like the run streak feature because it made me feel bad or disappointed with myself when I would miss a day.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Going through how to set up our headspace account and all the features on the app was very helpful
TherapyExplain_T3: I go to individual therapy once every other week for anxiety and stress management.
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned to take a step back and focus on things I can control when I am feeling overwhelmed.
HowNotes_T3: I have used these skills when I can feel my anxiety growing.
BarriersNotes_T3: I don't like that not all of the meditations have the option to adjust the duration.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I found the SOS pack to be the most helpful because they were short and supplied a nice space to refocus and calm down.

Comments: I really feel that the program has added value to my life. It took some time before I could see effects, but then my state of mind improved radically in a short period of time
SkillNotes_T2: You are not your thoughts was something I knew, but by hearing it in this context it changed a lot in my way of approaching my thoughts. Also, realizing that emotions come and go as thoughts do.
HowNotes_T2: When having difficult conversations with people important to me or when feelimg overwhelmed by my thoughts or emotions.
BarriersNotes_T2: Maybe the internet connection, but I haven't had trouble with that
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I liked the short lessons before the mindfulness practice of the Handlimg Sadness pack. I also found the short animations of impermanence and the blue sky or calm sea very valuable.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: Getting notifications like "remember the blue sky" were very valuable for me and I felt a sense of contentment.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I liked it how it was and I think it was helpful.

Comments: I really like the Smile study and the headspace program. I tend to do a meditation everyday and I feel it wakes me up and motivates me to get on with my day. I feel more connected to myself and the others around me. I definitely am more happy with the choices I am making and I feel headspace helps m
SkillNotes_T2: I have learned that before I am able to make a positive impact on anyone's life, I first have to make sure myself is happy and comfortable in my own life.
HowNotes_T2: When I am stressed out I have learned to take deep breaths and reevaluate what is happening, then start from the beginning and redo what I was doing in a calmer state.
HowNotes_T3: Whenever I feel stressed or like I cannot focus on my work, I am able to take a small break and do a short meditation to bring myself back to earth so I can realize what I’m doing and make myself determined to get to my goal.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: The basics pack was definitely the most helpful to me because I had never meditated before, and so the basics pack was a really nice way to get started. I really enjoyed getting into meditation and it has made me be able to start my day everyday much easier and with a much brighter, happier and motivated start.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: The content in the headspace app was a really nice way to get initiated into the art of meditation. It made me realize ways I can bring meditation into my everyday life. I also like the silent parts of the meditation where I can reflect on my own thoughts and feelings without any interruptions.

Comments: I have really enjoyed being able to be apart of this study so far. I haven't felt any significant change in my mental health or my feelings particularly when I'm trying to fall asleep, but I have been better able to cope with them when my thoughts start to spiral.
SkillNotes_T2: Headspace has helped me better get some sleep at night. I used to often lie awake at night, letting my thoughts go a mile a minute. But now with my Headspace techniques, I know how to sort of catch myself in those moments and take a minute to accept them, acknowledging that they happen, but knowing it'll be pass.
HowNotes_T2: I often use these skills to get better sleep. But I also use them when I'm starting to feel overwhelmed academically. Whether it be with thoughts of my future education, or feeling inadequate in my extracurriculars, I've been better able to recognize my negative thought patterns and sort of tell myself that it's ok to feel like that. Others may feel like that as well, and that is ok, so long as I do not let that thought pattern take over my life or ruin something for me.
BarriersNotes_T2: Not particularly, I feel like being mobile has made things much less stress inducing. While online school may not be particularly easy, the ease and casual environment of this study has helped me feel a lot better with it.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I often use the SOS tracks when I'm having a particularly hard time sleeping and they've been very helpful in getting my heart to stop racing so wildly. I guess I picked those tracks because they were just so appropriately named, it felt like in that moment I needed an SOS. I also enjoy the sleep casts/sounds, because I really enjoy having background noise to lull me to sleep. It helps keep my mind off of things that are negative to think about before I go to bed.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I really like using Headspace, it's a well designed app. The statistics section in particular always gives me motivation to practice because it's a little competition for myself. I love the Mindful Moments as well. They're often nice little reminders to take a breathe in the middle of my day when I feel mos
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: I think the orientation went really well. Telling us a little about how these techniques can be used in the real world, and experiences that others have had with them gave me hope that this could be a turning point in my stress levels for me. Actually setting up our Headspace accounts also helped me feel more confident in getting started with the study. I also really appreciated the copy of the slides because I'm a very visual learner.
SkillNotes_T3: I have become much better at putting things into perspective. I used to catastrophize a lot, but now I’m more capable of thinking of where I am in the moment and how what I’m feeling can impact that and how it can’t/what I can’t control through my emotions.
HowNotes_T3: I had this huge test coming up. And I ended up not performing as well as I would have liked. Instead of panicking like I used to, I had a brief moment of frustration but then I was able to sort of categorize what this would impact and what I can do to fix it rather than feel worse.
BarriersNotes_T3: I think just because it’s so remote I would sometimes forget, especially when I was feeling overwhelmed. So it was hard to practice sometimes. Maybe sending some gentle daily reminders would help.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I really enjoyed the basics pack as well as the group meditation practice. It made me feel a little more connected to others during a time when everyone feels rather distant. The SOS tools were the most helpful though I think. When my anxiety would start to overwhelm me these really helped bring me down and remember where I was.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I think the statistics tracker was one of the most helpful features in the app. I’m a really competitive person and so it was helpful to sort of make it a contest for myself. The reminders to practice were really helpful. But at times (when I was feeling particularly overwhelmed ironically) it was a little bit like hey I have bigger things going on I don’t have time for this.

PracticeNotes_T2: I do a meditation on youtube that I like. It's about 8 minutes long and I try to do it once a week at least. I make sure to plan out my day every day and reflect on what I have done and what I can improve on. It's a slow process, and it takes a long time
Comments: Sometimes I forget to use headspace, and I feel guilty because my goal was to do 10 minutes a day originally. I went like a week and half without touching the app because my life got super crazy.
SkillNotes_T2: Deep breathing is something I've gotten a lot better at, and tuning out outside noises and distractions. Headspace has helped me feel more at peace somewhat.
HowNotes_T2: I like to deep breathe when I get nervous or anxious about something and it helps me calm down. I do this when I'm studying and at home.
BarriersNotes_T2: No, not really.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I liked the minis of pain, anxiety, panic, etc. They helped me to calm down and not stress as much when I needed them. I don't really like the longer sessions because it's a lot of quiet and I can do that on my own. I like when I can hear someone talking and guiding me.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: I liked the run streak when I had it, but it made me less motivated when I lost it. It made me feel guilty for not keeping up with it, and when I feel guilty I tend to avoid it, so it was not beneficial to me. I'm trying to work on not doing that.
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: Everything was somewhat helpful for the most part! We needed to know what we were getting into and I appreciated the explanations and examples.
TherapyExplain_T3: November 12th, a 45 minutes session with my therapist. Depression was hitting me hard a
PracticeNotes_T3: Besides headspace, I use a specific youtube meditation that helps my body become calm and makes my mind at peace. I do it roughly every other day for about 10 minutes. I like sitting down and thinking about my day and what I
SkillNotes_T3: I have learned to accept myself a little more than before. Accepting my mistakes, my procrastination, etc and trying to help kyself do better than the day before. It's ok to not be productive sometimes, and it's ok to feel the way I do.
HowNotes_T3: When I feel myself getting upset, I temind myself that it will just take more of my time away and I can use that time to make myself feel better.
BarriersNotes_T3: Even with reminders on my phone,  I forget to use headspace a lot when I already have mindfulness techniques used throughout my day.
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I liked the daily headspace topics; they were different and intriguing most of the time. I also liked using the anxiety/panic ones to calm me down when I felt anxious and upset.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I ended up not liking the run streak. It made me feel bad when I lost it and I didn't have the motivation to continue it anymore. I felt guilty for not using headspace a lot towards the end of the study. I found my own mindfulness to be more helpful than headspace, so I focused on myself instead.

TherapyExplain_T2: Started individual therapy for depression and anxiety with a therapist. One hour session biweekly to talk through dai
Comments: I really enjoy that Headspace is personable in the sense that you can customize your experience in the app with the different categories and meditation time lengths.
SkillNotes_T2: A skill learned from the app is to acknowledge emotions like saddness and let it pass through. another skill is to be aware of what you are doing and the things around you, including your body. If you lose focus, just return yourself back into focus and become aware of it.
HowNotes_T2: During schoolwork and lectures, I remember to do things with awareness and attention instead mindlessly going through things. While sitting at my desk, I am aware of my body and the sensations I experience as I go about my work.
BarriersNotes_T2: I do not believe there is anything that makes it difficult to engage
ValuableComponentsNotes_T2: I liked the packs because you can choose different ones based on how you feel or your current situation. I mainly used the "handling sadness" and "self-esteem" packs which were helpful. I also used the group meditation live sessions a few times, and I thought that was really cool and interesting. Besides the mediation audios, I also listened to focus music in the app, which helped a lot while I was studying.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T2: So far, I think all the components/features of Headspace are really helpful to me as a user. I think the best part of Headspace is the variety of sessions, packs, etc because I think every person can find something for themselves that they can connect to. As of now, I do not see any features that were unple
ValuableOrientationNotes_T2: The most helpful parts of the orientation were the informational videos, discussions, and navigation through the app. The informational videos really helped to introduce me to mediation through Headspace, and the discussions were really interesting to see what other people were thinking as well. The demonstration and the workshop were incredibly helpful as well because it makes the user get a grip on how to get started with Headspace. I think every part of the orientati
TherapyExplain_T3: 1 hour individual therapy sessions for handling and dealing with depression and anxiety
SkillNotes_T3: Through Headspace, I learned to acknowledge emotions as they come and go, and I learned to not associate myself with these fleeting emotions because they are always changing. I also learned to not associate myself heavily with a low self-esteem because the idea can stick in my mind to think it is permanant.
HowNotes_T3: Often I find myself critisizing myself harshly, so I remember what I learned through Headspace. So, I recognize my emotions and thoughts, and I let them pass. I will also tell myself that everything is changing and can be changed which helps with negative emotions or negative feelings about myself.
BarriersNotes_T3: NA
ValuableComponentsNotes_T3: I really liked listening to the Handling Sadness and the Self-esteem course packs the most since they relate most to what I experience.
ValuableFeaturesNotes_T3: I really enjoy the variety in Headspace because there is always something for everyone. The Headspace notifications were also helpful to remind me everyday to check into the app and get me started with meditation.
TherapyExplain_T4: 1hour talk therapy sessions once every two weeks for depression and anxiety

Comments: I like how much freedom we were given throughout this study. Using headspace on my own time and when I truly needed to mediate was really helpful.
SkillNotes_T2: I have learned to try to deal with worries that are present and try to tackle them first instead of being overwhelmed and stressed about the future. I also learned to take 10 mins out of my day for myself to relax and mediate.
